30. arta—toga ‘ a toga of little breadth'. The toga seems unquestionably to have been osan oval form [cp. Rein in Becker’s Gallus3 111. 143], but folded, as a rule, along the greater axis of the ellipse. Hence in wearing it the breadth would be mea- sured from the shoulders downwards; and a toga, if too broad, would be either inclined to trail‚ or would be necessarily arranged in too elaborate folds. In Epod. lv. 8 Horace speaks of an ostentatious sellow Sacram metiente viam cum bis trium ulna· rum toga. Orelli is quite right in explaining this as ‘ toga quae propter longitudinem ad imos talos demissa metiatur viam, id est, eam semper tangat et radat ’, although Macleane, from not undet-standing the way in which a toga was arranged, rejects this view.
